"title": "5712: marriage, between God and his people",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5712",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Marriage is used to describe the relationship between God and Israel in the OT and between Jesus Christ and the church in the NT. Contemplating marriage deepens understanding of God's love for his people; examining God's covenant love for his people similarly enriches an understanding of marriage.</p>\n<h2>God's marriage relationship with Israel</h2>\n<h3>God's marriage covenant with Israel</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:8-Ezek16:14\">EZK 16:8–16:14</a></strong> <em>The covenant at Sinai was seen as a form of marriage.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer31:32\">JER 31:32</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:59-Ezek16:60\">EZK 16:59–16:60</a></p>\n<h3>God as Israel's husband</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa54:5\">ISA 54:5</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos2:7\">HOS 2:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Joel1:8\">JOL 1:8</a></p>\n<h3>Israel's early devotion</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer2:2\">JER 2:2</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:43\">EZK 16:43</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos2:15\">HOS 2:15</a></p>\n<h2>The breakdown of God's marriage to Israel</h2>\n<h3>Israel's adultery</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer3:20\">JER 3:20</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer2:32\">JER 2:32</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:32-Ezek16:34\">EZK 16:32–16:34</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos1:2\">HOS 1:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos9:1\">HOS 9:1</a></p>\n<h3>Israel's alienation from God is likened to a divorce</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos2:2\">HOS 2:2</a></strong> <em>Israel's unfaithfulness led to a form of divorce between God and his people. This was sometimes identified with the exile.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa50:1\">ISA 50:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer3:6-Jer3:10\">JER 3:6–3:10</a></p>\n<h2>The renewal of God's marriage to Israel</h2>\n<h3>God calls his bride to return</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer3:12-Jer3:14\">JER 3:12–3:14</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos3:1-Hos3:3\">HOS 3:1–3:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa54:6-Isa54:8\">ISA 54:6–54:8</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos2:14\">HOS 2:14</a></p>\n<h3>The renewed relationship</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa62:4-Isa62:5\">ISA 62:4–62:5</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer31:31-Jer31:33\">JER 31:31–31:33</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:62\">EZK 16:62</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos2:16\">HOS 2:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos2:19-Hos2:20\">HOS 2:19–2:20</a></p>\n<h2>Jesus Christ's marriage relationship with the church</h2>\n<h3>Jesus Christ's love as a model for marriage</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph5:25-Eph5:33\">EPH 5:25–5:33</a></strong></p>\n<h3>Jesus Christ is described as a bridegroom</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John3:29\">JHN 3:29</a></strong> <em>John the Baptist describes Jesus Christ as the bridegroom and himself as the best man.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt9:15\">MAT 9:15</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark2:19-Mark2:20\">MRK 2:19–2:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:34-Luke5:35\">LUK 5:34–5:35</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt22:2\">MAT 22:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt25:1-Matt25:13\">MAT 25:1–25:13</a></p>\n<h3>The church as Christ's bride</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor11:2\">2CO 11:2</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev19:7-Rev19:9\">REV 19:7–19:9</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev21:2\">REV 21:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev21:9-Rev21:10\">REV 21:9–21:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev22:17\">REV 22:17</a></p>",
